"\"Given the claim and the reference, you should answer whether the claim is true or false. \\\"Claim: there were no ice sheets covering either Greenland or West Antarctica, and much of the East Antarctic ice sheet was gone. Reference: \\\\n\\\\nRaymo, M. E., & Kuiper, K. F. (1992). From a glacial ocean to a deglacial sea: Late Quaternary paleoceanography of the North Atlantic. Paleoceanography, 7(4), 535-556.\\\\n\\\\nIn this study, Raymo and Kuiper reconstructed the paleocirculation of the North Atlantic Ocean during the last glacial maximum (LGM) and the subsequent deglaciation. They found that during the LGM, the North Atlantic was a cold, freshwater lake, with large ice sheets covering Greenland and West Antarctica. The ice sheets were so massive that they blocked the flow of warm water from the equator to the poles, resulting in a cold surface current that ran along the eastern coast of North America and Europe. As the climate warmed up at the end of the last Ice Age, the ice sheets melted and the ocean circulation changed dramatically. The authors suggest that the melting of the ice sheets and the resulting change in ocean circulation played a key role in the deglaciation of the North Atlantic region.\\\"\\n Response:  True.  Based on the information provided in the reference, it is clear that the claim is accurate. During the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM), large ice sheets did cover both Greenland and West Antarctica, and the North Atlantic was a cold, freshwater lake. As the climate warmed up at the end of the last Ice Age, these ice sheets melted, leading to significant changes in ocean circulation. Therefore, the claim that there were no ice sheets covering Greenland or West Antarctica, and much of the East Antarctic ice sheet was gone, is supported by the reference.\"\n"label: true
